Hi,<br>
<br>
Below, I attempt to mention the issues that were discussed this
morning. They will probably be a little confused as the discussion was
very wide ranging and mobile. I believe there were some action items
that I was able to note but I may have missed some. Please feel free to
comment and add items as appropriate.<br>
<ul>
  <li>The "monitoring" aspect of usability: need to replace several
features of monalisa, including jobs running, waiting, total slots,
etc. GIPs exist and do try to distinguish between VOs at least for
running / waiting jobs. On the subject of monitoring and <i>cemon</i>:
Plugins are a feature of cemon, but currently the only ones available
are LDIF-in (GIP) and LDIF (BDII) and ClassAd (Condor) out.<br>
  </li>
  <li>Troubleshooting team. Ruth said she thought my attendance at this
meeting was important going forward. Subsequent emails suggested I
should officially join the troubleshooting team and take an active part
in the usability campaign. I attended the meeting this afternoon. More
correspondence and interaction will be forthcoming. Shaowen to attend
Thursday 11am? Frank called while I was in meetings to coordinate
agenda: will mention this when we speak.<br>
  </li>
  <li>Meta-scheduling is a major usability issue, as is the overhead of
getting running on a new site.</li>
  <li>Client installation -- separation of submission and scheduling
functions -- submission from laptop? How to configure a laptop OSG
client to do this? Possible/ Running a scheduler is the responsibility
of the VO: authorization for remote submitters? What about submissions
to multiple VOs (and therefore multiple schedulers) from the same
laptop and/or user?</li>
  <li>Job Control -- Paul LeBrun's experience. CDF's jobmon? jobmon is
not batch-system agnostic. Difficult to imagine something that would be
agnostic without providing a whole toolkit (eg command-line, "<tt>send-command
&lt;command&gt; &lt;job-id&gt;</tt>", "<tt>process-command
&lt;job-id&gt;</tt>" and library API (<tt>process-command (void (*
callback(char const *command)</tt>). It would still end up
communicating by means of common filesystems, but at least the
mechanisms would be standardized and robust.<br>
  </li>
  <li>User documentation: both specifically on resource selection and
also at the lowest level on how to submit jobs on the OSG without using
any VO-provided tools or wrapper layers.</li>
  <li>Workload management system: Swift II aka VDS: Mike Wilde's baby.
I believe GADU is acting as "guinea pig" for this project.</li>
  <li>Exec-caching: Condor specific; goes based on name, no date or
checksum. Cache persists nominally until all jobs using that exec are
finished, but anecdotal evidence suggests the cache may persist for
some time (&gt;~ 1 hour, &lt; 1 day) afterwards.</li>
  <li>WBS year II:</li>
  <ul>
    <li>Site usability metrics;</li>
    <li>Fermilab vision for leadership -- a place in usability?</li>
  </ul>
  <li>Certificate problems: every user has to insert CAs for ESNET and
DOEGrids (and KCA for FNAL) into their browser (and email client) if
sending signed and/or encrypted emails is desired. ESNET recently (how
recently?)&nbsp; put out new certs (new hardware) and newly issued DOE certs
require them to validate the chain on browser import. Note that the
current "press button to import" method of obtaining personal certs
does *not* give helpful diagnostics if there is something wrong with
the email chain. Ruth wants GOC tickets for:</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Getting CAs into Microsoft and Firefox default CA lists.</li>
    <li>Making better diagnostics for "press button to import" -- can
the JS request the required CAs from the browser's store and direct the
user to an appropriate import page if not? Also, CA's are not given
suitable extensions such that click to import works.</li>
  </ol>
  <li>How do non-PP grids deal with certs? Biology? Portals.</li>
  <li>Sources of usability information for documentation, improvements
etc:</li>
  <ul>
    <li>Burt Holzman: very good dealing with problems and finding
solutions, but doesn't keep records -- someone would need to interview
&amp; tak notes?</li>
    <li>Me: page with everything dumped in for record? Scraped
regularly by (eg) Forrest for placement in appropriate documentation?</li>
    <li>Others?</li>
  </ul>
</ul>
That's as much as I have in my notes and memory; as I said, please feel
free to augment and/or correct.<br>
